CWTS Database Data Dictionary

07/03/2025

Database Overview

Disclaimer

The Coded Wire Tag System (CWTS) database is a work in progress and is subject to change.

Coded Wire Tag System (CWTS) Database

Coded-wire tag recovery information becomes part of the WDFW CWT Recovery Database from one of four sources: 1. The intact snout is delivered to the Tag Lab from samplers for coring, wire retrieval, and reading. 2. The wire, already dissected from a snout, is delivered to the Tag Lab. 3. Electronic tag result information is delivered to the Tag Lab or the Database Manager 4. Recovery records are created by the Database manager.

  1. Collection of snouts with coded-wire tags by samplers: Field samplers and others identify fish containing wire tags in their snouts either via the presence of an adipose fin clip (method in use through the late 1990’s) or by a device (hand-held wand or stationary tunnel) that detects the magnetic tag. The snout is cut off of these fish, just behind the eyes, and the fish head is labeled, bagged, and taken to the Tag Recovery Lab in Olympia. A sample label or form accompanies the snout throughout the Tag Lab process as data is recorded into the recovery database. The wire is usually attached to the label or form; then the label is filed. This is the source of most recovery records.

The Tag Recovery Lab processing steps: Frozen snouts are partially thawed and checked for the presence of a wire via a magnetic detector (V detector). If no wire is found, the snout is re-magnetized in case the wire has lost its magnetic moment. Snouts without wire are identified as “no tags” and recorded as such. If a wire is determined to be present, a cylindrical core is extracted in the likely location of the wire. The core is systematically dissected until the wire is found. Tag wires are attached to the accompanying snout label and then read under a microscope. The code on the tag and the type of tag are recorded. Periodically, the number of cores is recorded (the number of times the dissector had to core the head in order to find the wire) for assessing the incidence of misplaced tags. The Tag Lab staffs keys the tag reading, tag type, and the collection data for the snout into an electronic data file. As the data are entered, the entry program checks for valid data and for unlikely tag readings when compared to tag release information. Invalid or unlikely data results in an interruption in the entry program so that the data entry staff can reread the tag wire or re-enter invalid data. The entered data is re-keyed in a verification process by a different person from the data entry person.

  1. Wire, already read, delivered to the Tag Lab: The wire is re-read by the Tag Lab staff to validate the tag reading and assign the tag type. Any revisions are noted on the accompanying label or form. Sometimes the paper form is changed by the Tag Lab staff to fit with protocol for the fishery. The tag result information and collection information is then keyed into the recovery database. These records are also verified, as described above. Examples of fisheries where this occurs is Skagit River chinook spawning ground, Snake River sport steelhead, and Methow Hatchery spring chinook. For some WDFW hatchery recoveries, Tag Recovery Lab staff reads the snouts on-site.

  2. Wire and/or electronic recovery data submitted by other projects: The electronic data is reformatted and imported into the recovery database by the Database Manager. The Tag Recovery Lab staff reads the wire to validate the initial reading and to assign the tag type if needed. The Tag Lab then verifies the data and makes any needed corrections.
    An example of this is Lyons Ferry Hatchery Fall Chinook. Other projects include Ocean Treaty Troll by the Makah Tribe, region 3 Priest Rapids & Ringold Springs fall chinook, Mid-Upper Mainstem Columbia River FW sport, and Hanford Reach & Priest Pool spawning ground survey.

  3. Recoveries added by Database Manager: These are usually records where the snout did not reach the Tag Lab, but the sampling information indicates that CWT’d snouts were detected. This is most common for spawning ground survey recoveries, hatchery rack fish released upstream, and for stream trap recoveries where the CWT’d wild fish are noted but not sacrificed. No verification is performed by the Tag Lab.

CWTS Core Tables Schema

What are the core tables in the CWTS database? CWTS core data tables include expansion, recovery_group, and recovery_fish

  1. expansion contains catch, sample, and expansion (derived) data and is linked to the cwt_expansion_fish table to assign expansion factors to individual fish.
  2. recovery_group data describes the fishery, gear, time strata, species, and user groups for a sampling event and is linked to cwt_recovery_fish.
  3. recovery_fish contains individual fish data. When data providers enter data in the “Annual Data Entry” page of the SPI Web Funnel, this is where the data is stored.

Public Data Portal

CWTS data contained in this system is mirrored on the WDFW open data portal at https://www.data.wa.gov. The dataset can be accessed directly through the public web portal. Data is refreshed in this system nightly.

Contact Information

For more information, please contact the CWTS data manager Gil Lensegrav at gilbert.lensegrav@dfw.wa.gov .

result_type_lut

Lists possible outcomes for the tag wire in the processing a snout identified in the field as having a wire.

short_description description
Blank Wire Tag Tag is blank wire or agency-only wire
Decoded Tag Tag was decoded with no discrepancies
Lost Tag Tag was lost in lab process before reading
No Snout Snout identified as CWT but not processed
No Tag No tag wire was found in the snout
Tag Discrepancy Recovery data incompatible with release data
Unreadable Tag Complete code on the tag wire is unreadable
